::Communication Apprehension Definition::According to McCroskey (1977), what is communication apprehension?{
~The inability to speak clearly in public settings #This describes a speech impediment or articulation problem, not communication apprehension. McCroskey's definition focuses on fear/anxiety, not physical ability to speak.
=An individual's level of fear or anxiety associated with either real or anticipated communication with another person or persons #This is McCroskey's exact definition from his foundational 1977 paper. Communication apprehension is the fear or anxiety about communicating, whether the communication is happening now (real) or will happen later (anticipated).
~A personality disorder that prevents effective communication #McCroskey defined communication apprehension as a normal individual difference, not a disorder. 10-20% of people experience significant CA—it's common, not pathological.
~The physical symptoms of nervousness during presentations #While CA can cause physical symptoms (sweating, rapid heartbeat), McCroskey's definition focuses on the emotional state (fear/anxiety), not the symptoms themselves.
}

::Duarte's Three-Act Structure Components::What are the three parts of Duarte's presentation structure taught in this week's lecture?{
~Introduction, Analysis, Conclusion #"Introduction, Analysis, Conclusion" is a common essay structure, but Duarte's framework uses different terminology specifically for presentations.
~Hook, Body, Call to Action #While these are important presentation elements, they aren't Duarte's three-act terminology. The hook is part of the beginning, and call to action is part of the end.
=Beginning, Middle, End #Duarte's three-act structure consists of Beginning (establish "What Is"), Middle (oscillate between "What Is" and "What Could Be"), and End (paint the "New Bliss").
~Opening, Evidence, Closing #These are generic presentation terms. Duarte's specific framework is Beginning → Middle → End, adapted from Hollywood screenwriting.
}

::Opening Elements Identification::According to the lecture, which of the following is NOT one of the four elements of a strong opening?{
~Hook #Hook IS one of the four elements—it grabs attention with a statistic, question, story, or bold claim.
~Relevance #Relevance IS one of the four elements—it explains why this matters to THIS audience.
=Summary of main points #The four elements are Hook, Relevance, Credibility, and Roadmap (preview structure). While roadmap previews where you're going, a detailed summary of main points comes at the end, not the opening.
~Credibility #Credibility IS one of the four elements—it establishes why you're qualified to speak on this topic.
}

