::Anxiety vs Excitement Reframing::According to the lecture, anxiety and excitement are the same physiological state with different interpretations, and reframing anxiety as excitement is a research-backed technique for managing presentation nervousness.{
TRUE#The lecture cited Alison Wood Brooks' research from Harvard Business School showing that anxiety and excitement create identical physiological responses (increased heart rate, adrenaline). The difference is cognitive interpretation. Reframing "I'm anxious" as "I'm excited" is a mental preparation technique in the Anxiety Management Plan (AMP). This reframe works because you're not fighting your body's response—you're changing how you interpret it.#Actually, this is true. The lecture specifically mentioned reframing as part of the mental preparation component of the AMP, based on Brooks' HBS research. Both anxiety and excitement involve arousal; the label you apply determines the experience.
}

::Purpose of Oscillation in Middle Section::Why does Duarte's "Sparkline" pattern of oscillating between "What Is" and "What Could Be" work better than simply listing solutions?{
~It makes presentations longer and more detailed #Length is not the purpose. Oscillation creates engagement regardless of presentation length. The lecture emphasized that this pattern maintains attention, not extends duration.
=It creates emotional tension through contrast that maintains audience attention #The lecture explained that "contrast creates emotional tension that maintains attention." Each oscillation between current problems ("What Is") and future possibilities ("What Could Be") keeps the audience engaged by showing the gap and the solution repeatedly. The Steve Jobs iPhone example demonstrated this\: problem with old phones → solution with iPhone, repeated for each feature.
~It allows presenters to memorize their script more easily #Oscillation is about audience engagement, not presenter memorization. In fact, the lecture discouraged memorizing scripts word-for-word (sounds robotic).
~It reduces the need for visual aids #Oscillation is a content structure technique, unrelated to visual aid requirements. The lecture discussed visuals as a separate topic for Week 6.
}

::Authentic vs Inauthentic Communication::According to Brodsky's research cited in the lecture, what is the difference between adapting your communication style for context (e.g., showing respect to professors) and being inauthentic?{
~There is no difference—any adaptation is inauthentic #The lecture explicitly stated that "authenticity doesn't mean identical behavior in all contexts—it means genuine intent adapted to situation." Contextual adaptation is authentic.
=Adaptation maintains genuine intent while adjusting to situation; inauthenticity involves deception or faking #Brodsky's quote emphasized that "authentic communication is contextual." The lecture distinguished between adjusting tone to show cultural respect (authentic—your intent is genuine) versus delivering a memorized, robotic presentation (inauthentic—you're performing, not communicating). The key is whether your intent and content remain true, even as style adapts.
~Adaptation is only acceptable in Vietnamese culture #Contextual adaptation is universal, not culture-specific. While the lecture used Vietnamese culture as an example (adjusting for hierarchy), the principle applies globally.
~Authenticity requires identical behavior in all contexts #This contradicts Brodsky's research. Authenticity varies by channel and audience—being genuine doesn't mean being identical across all situations.
}

::Reading from Slides::Reading directly from slides improves audience engagement because it ensures you don't forget important points.{
FALSE#This is false. The lecture emphasized that reading from slides is a common presentation mistake that reduces engagement. When presenters read slides, audiences either (1) read ahead and stop listening, or (2) wonder why the presenter is needed at all. The lecture's "poor opening" example showed a presenter who merely recited slide content, which was boring and generic. Effective delivery requires knowing content well enough to speak naturally while slides provide visual support, not a script.#Actually, this is false. Reading from slides undermines engagement, not enhances it. The lecture distinguished between using slides as visual support (good) versus using them as a script (bad). Audiences can read faster than you speak—if you're just reading, they'll disengage. Preparation should make you confident enough to speak naturally, using slides as prompts, not scripts.
}

